  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 2.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "After",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " certain ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "years he went down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In lieu of the italic type \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "certain\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " here, the English idiom, \"years after,\" would aptly reproduce the facts of the case. This journey to Samaria to see Ahab was made in the seventeenth year of Jehoshaphat's reign (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:51",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 20:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). What were the precise antecedent circumstances of this visit of Jehoshaphat to Ahab it is interesting to surmise - whether it were the fruit of an invitation direct from Ahab, who had his own designs, or whether it were for diplomatic reasons, that worked in the mind of Jehoshaphat as well as of Ahab, in view of Syria. It is evident that Ahab promptly determined to improve this conference of kings. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Persuaded him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " he took steps to induce him. This is the uniform signification of the word here used in the eighteen times of its occurrence, and mostly in doubtful, or worse than doubtful, matter. The form is the hiph. of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "סוּת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in which conjugation only the verb occurs. The Revised Version renders \"moved.\" The visiting and cooperating of Jehoshaphat and Ahab made a novel departure in the history of the rended kingdoms of Judah and Israel, and continued till the time of Jehu. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Ramoth-Gilead",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This important city of Gad (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 20:8",
