  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The campaign undertaken along with Ahab against the Syrians at Ramoth in Gilead, with its origin, course, and results for Ahab, is narrated in 1 Kings in the history of Ahab) in agreement with our narrative, only the introduction to the war being different here. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:1-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is remarked, in connection with the preceding wars of Ahab with the Syrians, that after there had been no war for three years between Aram and Israel, in the third year Jehoshaphat king of Judah came up to the king of Israel; and the latter, when he and his servants had determined to snatch away from the Syrians the city Ramoth in Gilead, which belonged to Israel, called upon Jehoshaphat to march with him to the war against Ramoth. In the Chronicle the more exact statement, \"in the third year,\" which is intelligible only in connection with the earlier history of Ahab, is exchanged for the indefinite שׁנים לקץ, \"at the end of years;\" and mention is made of the festal entertainment which Ahab bestowed upon his guest and his train (עמּו אשׁר העם), to show the pains which Ahab took to induce King Jehoshaphat to take part in the proposed campaign. He killed sheep and oxen for him in abundance, ויסיתהוּ ,ecnadn, and enticed, seduced him to go up with him to Ramoth. הסית, to incite, entice to anything (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), frequently to evil; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. עלה, to advance upon a land or a city in a warlike sense. The account which follows of the preparations for the campaign by inquiring of prophets, and of the war itself, vv. 4-34, is in almost verbal agreement with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:5-35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Referring to 1 Kings or the commentary on the substance of the narrative, we will here only group together briefly the divergences. Instead of 400 men who were prophets, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we have about 400 men. It is a statement in round numbers, founded not upon exact enumeration, but upon an approximate estimate. Instead of אהדּל אם...הנלך, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in Kings, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", we have אהדּל אם...האלך, both verbs being in the same number; and so too in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where in Kings. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", both verbs stand in the plural, notwithstanding that the answer which follows, והצלח עלה, is addressed to Ahab alone, not to both the kings, while in the Chronicle the answer is given in the plural to both the kings, והצליחוּ עלוּ. in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"he prophesies me nothing good, but all his days (i.e., so long as he has been a prophet) evil,\" the meaning is intensified by the כּל־ימיו, which is not found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the ויושׁבים, which is introduced before the בּגרן, \"and sitting upon the threshing-floor,\" is due to difference of style, for it is quite superfluous for the signification. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the ambiguous words of Micah,' and Jahve will give into the hand of the king\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 22:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), are given in a more definite form: \"and they (the enemy) shall be given into your hand.\" In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 18:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in the first כּכה אמר זה, the אמר after the preceding ויּאמר is not only superfluous, but improper, and has probably come into the text by a copyist's error. We should therefore read only בּכה זה, corresponding to the כּכה זה of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
